'''Ramon Simpas Subejano''' (1905<U+2013>1988), a native of [[Philippines]], was a decorated [[United States]] [[World War II|WWII]] veteran.

==Biography==
Leaving the Philippines as a stowaway in 1927, he eventually became a [[United States Merchant Marines|merchant marine]].  Later purchasing a pool hall with casino winnings, he lost it during the [[Great Depression]], then worked as a busboy until he was [[Conscription in the United States#World War II|drafted in 1942]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Associated |last=Press |authorlink=The Associated Press |coauthors= |title=Ramon Subejano, 83; Hero of World War II |url=http://www.nytimes.com/1988/09/18/obituaries/ramon-subejano-83-hero-of-world-war-ii.html |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |date=September 18, 1988 |accessdate=June 4, 2009}}</ref><ref name="Taxi">{{cite web |url=http://www.taxi-usa.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2008-12.pdf |title=Remembering Ramon Subejano, a one man army |author=Al Livingston |date=December 2008 |work=Carriage News |publisher=taxi-usa.com |accessdate=29 January 2011}}</ref>

===World War II===
Pvt. Ramon S. Subejano served with Company A, 358th Infantry Regiment, 90th Infantry Division and saw combat at [[Operation Overlord|Normandy Beach]], [[Battle of the Bulge|Ardennes]], Northern [[France]], [[Holland]], and the [[Rhineland]].<ref name="Taxi"/>  He was a scout sniper and was wounded several times.  During the course of the war he earned 17 [[medal]]s, creditted for killing more than 400 [[Germany|Germans]] in [[battle]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Philippines' 2 Millennium History |last=Pancho Canlas |first=Luzano |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2000 |publisher=Buy Books |location= |isbn=9780741403230 |page=126 |pages=149 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=-IDNEunPyxcC&pg=PA126&lpg=PA126&dq=Ramon+Subejano&source=bl&ots=Mwdqg5iJe0&sig=KcyXJu3kcmnGYS__vhwEYKTyRQ8&hl=en&ei=15MnSpKQCYfCswPtypgf&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10 |accessdate=June 4, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ilonggo soldiers on other war fronts (2) |author=Atty. Rex S. Salvilla |newspaper=The News Today Online :: Iloilo News and Panay News |date=March 15, 2006 |url=http://www.thenewstoday.info/2006/03/15/ilonggo.soldiers.on.other.war.fronts.2.html |accessdate=December 8, 2009}}</ref> During one battle he was the sole survivor of his unit.<ref name="Taxi"/>

One of the medals was the [[Silver Star]] which cited him for "Gallantry in action on December 7, 1944 in the vicinity of Dillengen, Germany." The citation continued, "At the risk of his life, [[Private (rank)|Pvt.]] Subejano made his way along through devastating 20&nbsp;mm and [[machine gun]] fire and [[hand grenade]] explosions to the building. He then entered the strong point and going from room to room, killed five enemy, wounded six and forced the remaining 37 to surrender.<ref name="Taxi"/> At the end of the war he was flown to London for the victory parade, where he was presented to [[George VI of the United Kingdom|King George]] and [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]].<ref name="Taxi"/>

===Post-World War II===
Pvt. Ramon S. Subejano was featured in the front page of The New York Times on May 31, 1952 during the city's observance of Memorial Day. His picture appeared in the "A Salute To War Dead From A Decorated Hero" wearing his full dress army uniform complete with medals and ribbons he earned in the European and Pacific theaters rendering a salute in front of the [[Soldiers' and Sailors' Monument (New York)]]. According to The New York Times, he was an unscheduled addition to the Memorial Day program when he came as an spectator in uniform with his chest full of medals and ribbons, "hobbled up the monument steps using a cane and was introduced at the speaker's stand to the crowd" <ref>The New York Times May 31, 1952 http://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F70C1EFE3F5E177B93C3AA178ED85F468585F9 written by Amboytex Feb. 25, 2010</ref> He would later meet [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Edward Kennedy|Senator Kennedy]], and [[John F. Kennedy|President Kennedy]].<ref name="Taxi"/>
 
At one point his medals were stolen from his apartment; with the assistance of Senator Kennedy's office, the Department of Defense presented replacements of all his medals.<ref name="Taxi"/> In 1987, while living in the neighberhood of [[Brighton, Massachusetts|Brighton]] in the city of [[Boston]], he was charged threatening to harm his apartment manager.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sean |last=Murphy |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Elderly Man Charged With Threat Is Still A Hero In His Neighborhood |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8039768.html |work=Boston Globe |publisher=The New York Times Company |date=December 7, 1987 |accessdate=September 21, 2009}}</ref>  Less than a year later he would die in a [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Veteran Affairs]] Hospital in New York City.  Subejano is buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]]. His story is in the [[Library of Congress]], "One Man Army" (1978).<ref name="Arlington"/>

===Family===
Ramon was the oldest among the siblings, followed by Honorio Simpas Subejano. Then, Victorino Simpas Subejano lastly, Lucila Subejano Sabido.

